  <acceptance-criteria>
    <criterion testable="true">With a `playbook-embeddings` index containing an email playbook, "send this by email to John" returns a DispatchResult with Matched=true and ExtractedParameters containing "recipient"="John"</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">A message with no semantic match to any playbook returns DispatchResult with Matched=false</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">Total dispatch time (both stages) completes within 2 seconds under normal load (NFR-04)</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">When a single candidate has score &gt;= 0.85, Stage 2 LLM call is NOT made (verify via logging)</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">PlaybookDispatcher is NOT in the DI container registrations (factory instantiation only)</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">DispatchResult.OutputType and RequiresConfirmation are populated from the JPS definition (not hardcoded)</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">recordType pre-filter correctly excludes playbooks for other entity types from candidates</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">`dotnet build` passes with no errors</criterion>
  </acceptance-criteria>

  <notes>
    The `playbook-embeddings` index schema (from Task R2-003) should have fields: `id`, `playbookId`,
    `name`, `description`, `contentVector3072` (the embedding), `recordType`, `entityType`, `tags`.
    Confirm these field names before writing the search query — use the notes from R2-003 if available.

    For the Stage 2 LLM prompt, keep it very compact to stay within the 0.5s time budget. The prompt
    should be &lt;500 tokens: list candidates as a numbered JSON array and ask for structured selection.
    Do not include full playbook descriptions — just names and short tags.

    The LLM structured output for parameter extraction can use function calling / tool use if the
    IChatClient implementation supports it, or can use a JSON-constrained prompt. Check how
    `CompoundIntentDetector` handles structured output to follow the established pattern.
  </notes>

